Derek James wrote:

&gt;And we have some other questions:
&gt;
&gt;1) When the state is initialized for the double pole balancing trials,
&gt;0.07 is used as the value for one degree:
&gt;
&gt;	// Initialise state. 
&gt;	state[0] = state[1] = state[3] = state[4] = state[5] = 0;
&gt;	state[2] = 0.07; // one_degree;
&gt;
&gt;Is this a typo?  It is in both Ken and Colin&#39;s code.  
&gt;
Yeh this was pointed out recently on the list. It was probably a typo 
but it doesn&#39;t matter all that much so long as the starting angle isn&#39;t 
too big. I either mistakenly copied the typo or decided to keep the 
starting state the same as in Ken&#39;s code. For consistency you might want 
to leave it at 0.07 and put a comment explaining why.

&gt;2) When the environmental state values are normalized for input into
&gt;the network, they are handled differently in single and double pole
&gt;balancing.  For single:
&gt;
&gt;	// Provide state info to the network (normalised to 0 to 1.0).
&gt;	network.setInputSignal(0, (cart_pos_x + trackLength/2.0) / trackLength);
&gt;	network.setInputSignal(1, (cart_velocity_x + 0.75) /1.5);
&gt;	network.setInputSignal(2, (pole_angle + twelve_degrees) / twentyfour_degrees);
&gt;	network.setInputSignal(3, (pole_angular_velocity + 1.0) / 2.0);
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;For double:
&gt;
&gt;	network.setInputSignal(0, state[0] / trackLength);
&gt;	network.setInputSignal(1, state[1] / 2.0);
&gt;	network.setInputSignal(2, state[2] / 0.52);
&gt;	network.setInputSignal(3, state[3] / 2.0);
&gt;	network.setInputSignal(4, state[4] / 0.52);
&gt;	network.setInputSignal(5, state[5] / 2.0);
&gt;
&gt;Why are these different?
&gt;  
&gt;
Good question :)

The SP code seems to be rescaling to about 0 to 1(as the commentsays). 
Whereas the DP code is scaling by slightly different numbers but not 
adjusting into the 0-1 range, thus generating a range of (approx.) -1 to 
1. As it happens I don&#39;t think this really matters since the input 
signals can be scaled and their sign switched by the connection weights 
from the input nodes. As such you may want to leave them as they are, 
but again perhaps insert a comment explaining that the values are used 
for consistency,  assuming that my code duplicates Ken&#39;s.

&gt;For double it seems like you don&#39;t actually get values scaled between
&gt;0 and 1 or -1 and 1.
&gt;  
&gt;
It looks liek they&#39;re scaled to -1 to 1 to me.

&gt;3) Are 100,000 time steps necessary?  It seems to us that all networks
&gt;we&#39;ve looked at so far either fail or succeed very early in each
&gt;trial, (e.g., &lt;10,000 timesteps).  This would greatly increase
&gt;efficiency to truncate the amount of timesteps.
&gt;  
&gt;
I think you&#39;re right for all experiments except the anti-wiggle one. In 
that experiment I noticed some networks could keep the system stable for 
quite some time only to fail dramatically some time before the 100,000 
timesteps where up.

Colin
